20th Century Wind (near surface wind speed) 1901-2001</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/611061e5-dd3f-4612-b003-36120d0d35b2</link>     <description>The WATCH Forcing data is a twentieth century meteorological forcing dataset for land surface and hydrological models. It consists of three/six-hourly states of the weather for global half-degree land grid points. It was generated as part of the EU FP 6 project "WATCH" (WATer and global CHange") which ran from 2007-2011. The data was generated in 2 tranches with slightly different methodology: 1901-1957 and 1958-2001, but generally the dataset can be considered as continuous.  More details regarding the generation process can be found in the associated WATCH technical report and paper in J. Hydrometeorology.   To understand how the data grid is formed it is necessary to read the attached WFD-land-long-lat-z files either in NetCDF or DAT formats.   The data covers land points only and excludes the Antarctica.   Wind or near surface wind speed at 10m is the  near surface wind speed at 10m in m/s-1 at 6 hourly resolution and 0.5 x 0.5 degrees spatial resolution. </description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Dan Wright</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Atmospheric conditions</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Meteorological geographical features</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Global</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>World</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>6-hourly</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Atmosphere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>land surface</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>EU-FP6</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH_Project_NEC04264</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Wind</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Wind speed</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Hydrology</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Land surface modelling</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>meteorology</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2012-01-03T14:45:00Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/8ebdd74c-ffec-4d5f-b832-e4916df694c8">     <title>WATCH Forcing Data (WFD) - 20th Century PSurf (Surface pressure) 1901-2001</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/8ebdd74c-ffec-4d5f-b832-e4916df694c8</link>     <description>The WATCH Forcing data is a twentieth century meteorological forcing dataset for land surface and hydrological models. The data covers land points only and excludes the Antarctica.   Snowf or snowfall is the snowfall rate based on the GPCC bias corrected, undercatch corrected measured in kg/m2/s at 3 hourly resolution averaged over the next 3 hours and at 0.5 x 0.5 degrees spatial resolution.   Please note that there is also a WFD Snowf CRU bias corrected dataset, but as the GPCC dataset is the preferred dataset only this snowfall dataset is available from this gateway. These snowfall datasets contain snowfall data only and need to be combined with the respective WFD rainfall datasets to obtain precipitation data.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Dan Wright</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Atmospheric conditions</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Meteorological geographical features</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Global</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>World</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>3-hourly</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Atmosphere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>land surface</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>EU-FP6</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH_Project_NEC04264</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Snowf</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Snowfall rate</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Hydrology</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Land surface modelling</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>meteorology</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2012-01-03T14:45:00Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/e5d00d66-dcf5-4b0e-9346-f6205a336385">     <title>WATCH Forcing Data (WFD) - 20th Century  LWdown (Surface incident longwave radiation) 1901-2001</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/e5d00d66-dcf5-4b0e-9346-f6205a336385</link>     <description>The WATCH Forcing data is a twentieth century meteorological forcing dataset for land surface and hydrological models. The data covers land points only and excludes the Antarctica.   LWdown or surface incident longwave radiation (also known as downwards long-wave radiation flux ) is the surface incident longwave radiation averaged over the next six hours, measured in W/m2 at 6 hourly resolution and 0.5 x 0.5 degrees spatial resolution. </description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Dan Wright</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Atmospheric conditions</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Meteorological geographical features</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Global</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>World</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>6-hourly</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Atmosphere</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>land surface</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Water Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>EU-FP6</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH_Project_NEC04264</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>LWdown</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Surface incident longwave radiation</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Downwards long-wave radiation flux</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Hydrology</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Land surface modelling</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>meteorology</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2012-01-03T14:45:00Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/cd7db09f-edf6-4b06-b878-f1be6c649e3a">     <title>Conwy Catchment - Nant Y Brwyn Discharge dataset</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/cd7db09f-edf6-4b06-b878-f1be6c649e3a</link>     <description>Discharge data and in-stream temperature for a peatland headwater stream of the Conwy catchment, North Wales are presented from march 2008 until present. The stream for which the data represents is the Nant y Brwyn situated on the Migneint blanket bog within Snowdonia National Park. The purpose of the data is to calculate annual run-off estimates for the Nant y Brwyn catchment and to provide support for estimating fluvial carbon fluxes. Note: there are gaps in this data set due to equipment/battery failures and/or freezing of the stream.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Dan Wright</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Hydrometry</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Conwy Catchment</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Wales</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>UK</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>stream</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>continuous</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Biogeochemistry Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Project NEC04016 T3</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Water Resources</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2012-01-03T14:25:00Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/7bb6c7df-7630-4621-a0d4-eacc3ec2202b">     <title>Conwy Catchment - Llyn Conwy water temperature profile data</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/7bb6c7df-7630-4621-a0d4-eacc3ec2202b</link>     <description>In-lake temperature data for a peatland headwater lake of the Conwy catchment, North Wales are presented from November 2006 until December 2008. The Lake for which the data represents is Llyn Conwy situated on the Migneint blanket bog within Snowdonia National Park. The data is from a temperature string suspended from a buoy anchored above the deepest part of the lake. Temperature is recorded at 2m intervals throughout the lake profile from 1 to 19m. The purpose of this data is to investigate water column stability and to determine when, and to what degree stratification/mixing occurs and to make inferences about the effect of this on productivity, nutrient and chemical cycling. Note: there are gaps in this data set due to equipment/battery failures and/or freezing of the lake surface which meant it was not accessible.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Dan Wright</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>limnology</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Conwy Catchment</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Wales</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>UK</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>lake</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>continuous</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Biogeochemistry Programme</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>CEH Project C03715</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>T3</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2012-01-03T13:35:00Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     <item rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/dc33a786-9798-4ef3-9e66-22707ae40d67">     <title>Chemistry of iron in freshwaters of Northwest England</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/dc33a786-9798-4ef3-9e66-22707ae40d67</link>     <description>Chemical composition of freshwater samples from sites in Northern England. rdf:about="http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/ed90df1b-462c-46bb-afbd-59794fb03f6b">     <title>Elemental concentrations in fish from lakes in Northwest England</title>     <link>http://eidchub.ceh.ac.uk/metadata/ed90df1b-462c-46bb-afbd-59794fb03f6b</link>     <description>Data comprise concentrations of elements in ashed fish sampled from lakes in the English Lake District in 2012 and 2013. Fish were collected  from three lakes (Windermere, Bassenthwaite Lake and Derwent Water) by the Centre for Ecology & Hydrology (CEH) Lake Ecosystems group. Fish species collected were Roach (Rutilus rutilus), Perch (Perca fluviatilis), Ruffe (Gymnocephalus cernua), Trout (Salmo trutta), Pike (Esox Lucius) and Vendace (Coregonus vandesius). All samples were ashed prior to analysis by ICPMS or ICPOES to determine elemental concentrations.</description>          <dc:publisher>No publisher</dc:publisher>     <dc:creator>Jacky Chaplow</dc:creator>     <dc:rights></dc:rights>            <dc:subject>Environmental monitoring facilities</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Radioecology</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>deposition</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>radioactive</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>contamination</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>radionuclide</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>radiocaesium</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Northwest England</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>NERC_DDC</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>STAR_NOE</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>fish</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Roach</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Rutilus rutilus</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Perch</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Perca fluviatilis</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Ruffe</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Gymnocephalus cernua</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Trout</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Salmo trutta</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Pike</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Esox Lucius</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Vendace</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Coregonus vandesius</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Pollution and environmental risk</dc:subject>                 <dc:subject>Pollution & Environmental Risk</dc:subject>          <dc:date>2015-03-03T13:58:17Z</dc:date>     <dc:type>EIDC Document Container</dc:type>   </item>     </rdf:RDF>
